blocks.content: The representations of a nonnegative ` m ` as the sum of ` s ` nonnegative integers from a set ` b ` . Cf. Definition of [Nathanson] p. 123. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 1-Dec-2021.)
blocks.origin:
axiom df-repr(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, setvar s4) {
  |- wceq(crepr, cmpt(s0, cn0, cmpo(s1, s2, cpw(cn), cz, crab(s3, co(cv(s1), cmap, co(nat0, cfzo, cv(s0))), wceq(csu(s4, co(nat0, cfzo, cv(s0)), cfv(cv(s3), cv(s4))), cv(s2))))))
  -| diffss(s1, s4)
  -| diffss(s3, s4)
  -| diffss(s2, s4)
  -| diffss(s0, s4)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
}

thm breprexplemb(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wcel(cfv(cfv(c0, c1), c2), cc))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c3, cn0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c4, cn0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c5, cc))
  -| wi(w0, wf(c0, co(nat0, cfzo, c4), co(cc, cmap, cn)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, co(nat0, cfzo, c4)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, cn))
} = {
  a1ii(wi(w0, wcel(cfv(cfv(c0, c1), c2), cc)), wi(w0, wcel(c3, cn0)))
  a1ii(wi(w0, wcel(cfv(cfv(c0, c1), c2), cc)), wi(w0, wcel(c4, cn0)))
  a1ii(wi(w0, wcel(cfv(cfv(c0, c1), c2), cc)), wi(w0, wcel(c5, cc)))
  ffvelrnd(cfv(c0, c1), c2, cc, cn, w0)
  sylib(w0, wf(cfv(c0, c1), cn, cc), wcel(cfv(c0, c1), co(cc, cmap, cn)))
  ffvelrnd(c0, c1, co(cc, cmap, cn), co(nat0, cfzo, c4), w0)
  elmap(cfv(c0, c1), cc, cn)
  cnex()
  nnex()
}

blocks.name: breprexp
blocks.content: Express the ` S ` th power of the finite series in terms of the number of representations of integers ` m ` as sums of ` S ` terms. This is a general formulation which allows logarithmic weighting of the sums (see https://mathoverflow.net/questions/253246) and a mix of different smoothing functions taken into account in ` L ` . See ~ breprexpnat for the simple case presented in the proposition of [Nathanson] p. 123. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 6-Dec-2021.)
